passages.text: 2QF26 Indicates Stronger Forward- Looking Metrics; Encouraging Mid- Term Bm Margin Envisages S&M Cost Optimization

All forward- looking metrics (especially billings and cRPO) appear to be improving - a sign of higher customer commitments despite a relatively challenging macro. We also liked acceleration of AECO CC revenue growth and were encouraged by CEO's comments that they are seeing incremental strength in data centers, industrial buildings, and infrastructure projects. CFO used the opportunity to provide fiscal 2029EBIT margin target of \(41\%\) ahead of the typical ADSK University (later this month) and Investor Day on 10/07. We establish a Dec- 26 PT of \(\) 319\(, an 8% increase, and see a positive read- across for the space from today's results release.
- Beat on revenue; ahead on EBIT. ADSK reported 2QF26 revenue/EBIT margin of \(\) 1,763M/39\%\(compared to JPME of\) \ \(1,729M / 38\%\) and the Street's \(\) 1,724M/38\%\$

- Bright spots: 1) Billings growth accelerated to \(34\%\) yoy in CC (vs. \(30\%\) in 1QF26), coming in \(8\%\) ahead of consensus; the metric also grew faster excl new transaction model (26% yoy in 2QF26 vs. \(22\%\) in 1QF26); we expect billings to lap the effect of M&A starting from 3QF26E (meaning weaker growth dynamics in 2H of the year); Management raised CC billings growth outlook for the year to \(18\%\) at mid-point (up 1pp vs. 3M ago), supported by continued strength in net revenue retention (excluding the impact NRR would have remained within the historic \(100\% - 110\%\) range); 2) Direct sales reached \(62\%\) in 2QF26 (vs. \(55\%\) in 1QF26 and \(40\%\) in 2QF25) as transaction model transition continues to perform ahead of expectations; 3) Revenue grew \(18\%\) yoy on CC basis (vs. \(16\%\) yoy growth in 1QF26); excluding the new transaction model CC revenue grew \(11\%\) yoy (broadly similar to the 1QF25 level); growth acceleration was supported by the strength in AECO segment (half of total revenue), which grew \(24\%\) yoy in CC (up from \(21\%\) in 1QF26) - came in \(6\%\) above consensus. 4) Management 3QF26E forecasts are a touch above consensus and ADSK also raised FY26E outlook with all metrics above Street estimates - we specifically highlight that the revenue raise was visibly higher than the quarterly beat. 4) Second quarter in a row management raised the lower end of the EBIT margin narrowing it to \(\sim 37\%\) in CC; more importantly on the earnings call CFO provided EBIT margin guidance for Fiscal 2029E, setting the outlook to \(41\%\) ; CFO also flagged that FCF margin improvement should correlate closely with EBIT margin expansion

- Ornery mood: 1) While we are encouraged by CFO providing greater confidence in operating leverage and S&M efficiencies that gave ADSK confidence to roll out Fiscal 2029E EBIT margin target, management flagged that margin expansion will not be linear and the company will continue to face incremental headwinds to margins from transactional model transition in Fiscal 2027E; 2) Revenue growth of the "Make" segment (11% of total

- JPM reaction: Reiterate Neutral, with have incorporated 2QF26 beat, a more pronounced guidance raise and new fiscal 2029E margin forecasts into our model. With the release we are also establishing a December 2026 price target of \$319/sh (vs. \$296/sh end-25E previously). At our new price target, ADSK would trade at 9x Calendar Year 2026 EV/sales, 21x EV/EBITDA and offer almost \(4\%\) FCF yield. Despite incrementally better performance in the quarter, we reiterate our relative Neutral rating on the shares as we see better opportunity to play vertical SaaS space.

Autodesk (Neutral; Price Target: \(\) 319.00\$

Autodesk (ADSK) is connecting workflows in the cloud across three key verticals: AEC (architectural, engineering, and construction), manufacturing, and M&E (media & entertainment). ADSK's focus is ensuring that customers, suppliers, and other stakeholders can all communicate in a more uniform way. The company is highly acquisitive, using acquisitions to expand into new sub- segments such as water infrastructure with its 2021 acquisition of Innovyze for over \(\) 1B\$ . The company is in the midst of its transition to a transaction model, which enables a more direct sales motion, better customer visibility, and enhanced opportunity for cross- sell. While this transition makes sense, revenue growth adjusted for new transaction model appears underwhelming. We view Autodesk valuation as reasonable relative to our vertical SaaS coverage and other names in the industrial/ construction software space, which supports a Neutral rating.

December 2026 price target at \(\) 319\(. Our Dec 2026 DCF - based price target of\) \ \(319 / \mathrm{sh}\) is based on our 10- year DCF analysis (applying a \(\sim 11\%\) WACC and \(2\%\) terminal growth rate). At our price target, ADSK would trade at 9x 2026 EV/Sales.
Over half of revenue is international. ADSK could face headwinds from potential trade wars, given its relatively high international exposure compared to the rest of our coverage.

Pricing power risk. ADSK has leading market position within core AEC franchise and highly- recurring, subscription revenue base. However should competitive dynamic become less favorable, we see risking to sustained pricing power.

Revenue is concentrated among a small number of solutions. A substantial portion of revenue (over \(25\%\) ) is derived from AutoCAD, related offerings, and those that are interoperable with AutoCAD. Should any factor materially affect the market for CAD solutions, ADSK could face challenges.

Concentration among resellers. Autodesk has two main resellers which comprise \(\sim 40\%\) of sales, and nearly \(60\%\) of revenue comes through indirect channels. Should there be harm to reseller relationships with Autodesk not simultaneously improving direct sales, growth could suffer.

New CFO could strengthen transactional business. Although many are skeptical of new CFO's capabilities given affirmation and subsequent miss of guide when at Elastic, Autodesk is much more subscription focused. New CFO could help further scale the transactional portion of the business as the company continues to invest in complex AI capabilities.
High hopes for Analyst Day later this year. Considering that historically ADSK missed some of their long- term commitments, investors are eager to hear refresh of financial targets
at Autodesk Investor Day later this year.

More generous capital allocation. While Autodesk management is guiding for an increase of dollar buyback to \(\sim\) 1.2B in fiscal 2026E, we see room for positive surprise considering that the company is looking to generate over \(\mathbb{S}2\mathbb{B}\) in FCF for the same period.

Attractive opportunity in cloud. Should ADSK continue delivering accelerated level of win rates within the Construction portion of the cycle, headline revenue growth could see positive growth tailwinds.

BIM mandates could proliferate. Should BIM mandates proliferate, more public sector customers like DOTs could look to software like Autodesk to fulfill these mandates, making a build more efficient as infrastructure often faces limited resources.
